{"batchcomplete": "", "query": {"pages": {"42949642": {"pageid": 42949642, "ns": 0, "title": "Nicholas Vreeland", "contentmodel": "wikitext", "pagelanguage": "en", "pagelanguagehtmlcode": "en", "pagelanguagedir": "ltr", "touched": "2026-02-21T03:11:58Z", "lastrevid": 1315071578, "length": 18435, "fullurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Vreeland", "editurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Nicholas_Vreeland&action=edit", "canonicalurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Vreeland", "pageprops": {"defaultsort": "Vreeland, Nicholas", "page_image_free": "HHDL_Rato_hires002.jpg", "wikibase-shortdesc": "Swiss American Buddhist monk", "wikibase_item": "Q3339682"}, "description": "Swiss American Buddhist monk", "descriptionsource": "local", "extract": "Nicholas Vreeland, also known as Rato Khensur Thupten Lhundup, is a Tibetan Buddhist monk and the former abbot of Rato Dratsang, a 14th-century Tibetan Buddhist monastery reestablished in India. Vreeland is also a photographer. He is the son of Ambassador Frederick Vreeland and grandson of Diana Vreeland, former editor-in-chief of Vogue magazine and special consultant to The Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume Institute, where she set the \"standard for costume exhibitions globally.\"\nVreeland spends his time between India and the United States, where he is the Director of Kunkhyab Thardo Ling—The Tibet Center, New York City's oldest Tibetan Buddhist center. He is also the first Westerner His Holiness the Dalai Lama appointed Abbot of a Tibetan Buddhist monastery, one of the important Tibetan government monasteries under his authority.\nMonk with a Camera, a documentary film about Vreeland, was released in 2014.", "categories": [{"ns": 14, "title": "Category:1955 births"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:20th-century American Buddhists"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:20th-century American monks"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:20th-century Buddhist monks"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-centur